FR940426-2-00062 FR940426-2-00042 Determinations Regarding Eligibility To Apply for Worker Adjustment Assistance and NAFTA Transitional Adjustment Assistance In accordance with section 223 of the Trade Act of 1974, as amended, the Department of Labor herein presents summaries of determinations regarding eligibility to apply for trade adjustment assistance for workers (TA&hyph;W) issued during the period of April, 1994. In order for an affirmative determination to be made and a certification of eligibility to apply for worker adjustment assistance to be issued, each of the group eligibility requirements of section 222 of the Act must be met. (1) That a significant number or proportion of the workers in the workers' firm, or an appropriate subdivision thereof, have become totally or partially separated, (2) That sales or production, or both, of the firm or subdivision have decreased absolutely, and (3) That increases of imports of articles like or directly competitive with articles produced by the firm or appropriate subdivision have contributed importantly to the separations, or threat thereof, and to the absolute decline in sales or production. Negative Determinations for Worker Adjustment Assistance In each of the following cases the investigation revealed that criterion (3) has not been met. A survey of customers indicated that increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,399; Jefferson Smurfit Corp., Lancaster, NY TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,386; Reynolds Metals Co., Torrance Extrusion Plant, Torrance, CA TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,421; Kraft General Foods, Avon, NY TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,271; Leeds & Northrup Co., North Wales, PA In the following cases, the investigation revealed that the criteria for eligibility have not been met for the reasons specified. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,520; Black & Decker Co., Inc., Reconditioning Plant, Columbus, OH Increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,548; Clifton Precision Div., Clifton Heights, PA Increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,310; Arley Corp., DBA Century Curtain, Pinebluff, NC Increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,353; General Electric Corp., Evendale Plant, Cincinnati, OH U.S. imports of turbojet engines for aircraft declined in 1992 compared to 1991 and in the twelve month period of November&hyph;October 1992&hyph;1993 compared to the same period one year earlier. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,566; Digital Equipment, Franklin, MA The investigation revealed that criterion (2) has not been met. Sales or production did not decline during the relevant period for certification. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,493; Raytheon Equipment Div., Weltham, MA U.S. imports of radar apparatus declined in the November through October 1992&hyph;1993 period. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,473; Smith Industries, Houston, TX U.S. imports of oilfield machinery are negligible during the relevant period. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,592; Valdese Textiles, Inc., New York, NY The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,424; Jay-Lan Corp., Hays, KS The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,455; Amerada Hess Corp., Purvis Refinery, Purvis, MS U.S. imports of refined petroleum products declined absolutely and relative to domestic shipments in the twelve month period December 1992 through November 1993 as compared to the same period a year earlier. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,488; North American Refractories Co., Cleveland, OH The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,580; GTE Government Systems Corp., Needham, MA The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,489; Rowe International, Inc., Whippany, NJ The investigation revealed that any separations at the subject firm were due to a corporate decision to cease operations at that facility and transfer production to another domestic company-owned plant. Affirmative Determinations for Worker Adjustment Assistance TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,490; Seli Manufacturing, Inc., Scranton, PA A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after January 27, 1993.
